WEBVTT

00:07.234 --> 00:07.805
going to need that.

00:08.763 --> 00:09.394
Good morning.

00:10.594 --> 00:11.735
Good to be with you this morning.

00:12.616 --> 00:15.699
We are talking a lot about transformation these days.

00:15.739 --> 00:22.005
We're gonna keep talking about it today, but then also, I hope you're planning on joining us after the service.

00:22.045 --> 00:36.999
We've got some food downstairs, a light lunch, and we wanna talk about the life of the church, what our vision, our values are, and what we hope for in the coming year, and how we hope you will participate in that.

00:38.160 --> 00:40.402
When I think about transformation,

00:40.514 --> 00:46.804
I think about it personally, like what it means for me and for you the individual.

00:47.585 --> 00:57.601
I think about it like corporately about your marriages or you as a mom or dad or maybe it's a boss as a leader of some kind.

00:58.643 --> 01:00.385
I think about it corporately as a church.

01:00.646 --> 01:04.091
Like what would it mean for us to be a transformed church?

01:05.053 --> 01:08.338
And then ultimately, and I think this is God's mission,

01:08.418 --> 01:14.127
from Genesis to Revelation is how can we transform this world that has been fallen.

01:15.489 --> 01:16.431
So this is what we're doing.

01:16.871 --> 01:17.613
No small project.

01:18.815 --> 01:19.576
Let's start with prayer.

01:20.437 --> 01:27.629
Heavenly Father, we invite you into this place and into our hearts and into our mind.

01:29.832 --> 01:36.082
We take a deep breath, giving you our anxieties and our worries.

01:36.514 --> 01:46.286
Our concerns, the things that have weighed us down, the things that have hurt us and caused us pain.

01:47.788 --> 01:49.950
God, we hand those to you.

01:49.970 --> 01:54.135
One, because you are the one who can heal them.

01:54.195 --> 01:59.542
And two, because right now, those are not serving us.

02:00.803 --> 02:03.126
Right now, we need a word from you.

02:04.067 --> 02:06.290
We need that breath in our lungs.

02:06.370 --> 02:08.112
we need to be changed by you.

02:08.913 --> 02:10.435
So this is what we seek.

02:10.455 --> 02:13.238
In Christ's name we pray, amen.

02:13.258 --> 02:33.763
All right, we, at the risk of contradicting myself, last week, if you recall, the sermon was about Ephesians chapter four, and I said, your problem is that you're too old and you need to become young again.

02:33.783 --> 02:35.986
Do you remember this?

02:36.162 --> 03:01.778
Hopefully, so the idea being like we need a renewed heart, right, to meet made young again, and the problem is that we have these hearts that have calluses and that have become ossified and calcified, and we have an osteoporosis of the heart, and we need to rip off the calluses and become young again.

03:03.586 --> 03:13.248
At the risk of contradicting myself, today's message starts with, you're too immature and you need to become older and more mature.

03:13.308 --> 03:19.282
Paul says this too.

03:19.362 --> 03:23.707
In a few places, he actually chastises his congregations.

03:24.548 --> 03:29.794
One in Corinthians, and then whoever writes the letter to the Hebrews, they say it this way.

03:30.314 --> 03:33.558
First Corinthians 3-1 through three goes like this.

03:34.199 --> 03:43.289
Brothers and sisters, I can't speak to you as spiritual people, but instead as people of the flesh as infants in Christ.

03:44.390 --> 03:46.853
Infants, he calls them.

03:46.873 --> 03:48.114
I fed you milk.

03:48.258 --> 03:52.003
not solid food for you were not yet ready.

03:52.043 --> 03:57.751
In fact, you are still not ready for you are still influenced by the flesh.

03:58.231 --> 04:15.154
For since there is, and here he names two things that he's seeing in this congregation in Corinth, he says, since there's still jealousy and dissension among you, you are not influenced by the flesh and behaving like

04:15.234 --> 04:18.679
Are you not influenced by the flesh and behaving like unregenerate people?

04:19.521 --> 04:26.411
So he comes after them, and his key critique is, why aren't you more grown up?

04:27.192 --> 04:28.635
Why are you still infants?

04:29.276 --> 04:33.362
And at this point, you should be much older in your faith.

04:34.306 --> 04:52.754
If you are coming on Wednesday evenings, and if you're not, here's a bit of a plug, the emotional, healthy spirituality class we started this past Wednesday, there was a quote in there from one of the gentlemen who had participated in the class from before.

04:52.894 --> 04:59.224
And he said, I had been a Christian for 22 years.

05:00.146 --> 05:03.090
And instead of being a 22 year old Christian,

05:03.522 --> 05:12.534
I was just a one-year-old Christian 22 times, which is precisely what Paul's saying in 1 Corinthians, right?

05:13.055 --> 05:26.994
And it's maybe my concern for all of us that somehow, despite being in the faith for five years, 10 years, 40 years more, right?

05:28.002 --> 05:34.352
We end up with faiths that are just repeating the same here over and over and over again.

05:34.392 --> 05:48.514
And so I'd submit to you that just because you've been in the church for 80 years, we'll say, doesn't necessarily buy on its face that number doesn't make you an 80-year-old Christian.

05:48.574 --> 05:56.626
And so my deep concern is that the church worldwide, actually, especially in America here,

05:57.090 --> 06:07.222
has a bunch of infant Christians running around, acting as if they are mature Christians simply because they've been in the church long enough.

06:08.384 --> 06:13.610
I do not want this for Southrend Baptist Church, and I certainly don't want this for each of you.

06:13.650 --> 06:26.386
And so today's message is about how we can all grow up in the faith and put behind our infant ways and become mature Christians that Paul is calling us into.

06:28.962 --> 06:31.504
What I just said there was the nice way of saying it.

06:34.027 --> 06:37.470
If I could dig a little deeper, it would go this way.

06:37.530 --> 06:48.661
If I could poke even more like poignantly at each of you, I would say it this way.

06:52.285 --> 06:57.970
Maturity in Christ is a sign that you

06:58.146 --> 07:01.210
are walking in the way of Jesus.

07:02.592 --> 07:05.696
And we all know it when we see it, what that maturity looks like.

07:06.356 --> 07:13.926
But maturity is a sign you are walking in the way of Jesus, that you're being discipled by Jesus.

07:14.987 --> 07:26.642
And if you are not growing, if indeed you are living a life where just like for 40 years, you're a one year old Christian over and over again,

07:27.426 --> 07:37.035
then you should stop and ask yourself, am I even following Jesus or am I just going through some church motions?

07:40.379 --> 07:48.346
If you're a 40-year-old Christian and still acting like a toddler, this is no longer a personality quirk.

07:50.108 --> 07:52.190
You can't just simply say, this is who I am.

07:52.210 --> 07:56.434
I can't say it anymore clearly than this.

07:56.962 --> 07:58.904
You're simply living in sin.

07:58.964 --> 08:05.631
It is a sin of omission probably, but it is a sin nonetheless.

08:05.652 --> 08:12.119
A sin of negligence, a lack of care in your own growth.

08:15.042 --> 08:26.194
And when I look around the Christian landscape in the United States, I see that the church seems to have made it very comfortable for those 40-year-old Christians to remain infants

08:27.394 --> 08:30.277
And I think it has risen to the level of a crisis.

08:31.779 --> 08:38.186
So let me be clear, maturity and growth is not about becoming more powerful.

08:39.187 --> 08:45.094
It's not about becoming more successful or popular or whatever worldly standard you might put to it.

08:46.315 --> 08:55.986
Maturity looks like humility of all things, but mostly it looks like Christ, leading with a servant's heart.

08:56.706 --> 08:57.847
the things Jesus did.

08:59.429 --> 09:12.305
And if you're 40 years into your faith journey, and you're not really that much closer to looking like Jesus than you were 20 years ago, or 30, or even 40 years ago, then we've got a real problem on our hands.

09:13.226 --> 09:19.614
And I hope today will be a day where you take seriously the call into discipleship.

09:20.896 --> 09:24.360
And I want to offer you a tool on how to do this.

09:24.800 --> 09:26.162
We'll get there momentarily.

09:29.122 --> 09:36.070
400 years before Jesus lived, there was a man named Socrates who you've probably heard of.

09:37.151 --> 09:39.774
And he had any number of wise things to say.

09:39.794 --> 09:42.798
He kicked off Western philosophy as we know it.

09:43.499 --> 09:48.444
But one of them is that the unexamined life is not worth living.

09:48.504 --> 09:50.186
Who has heard this phrase?

09:50.307 --> 09:53.330
The unexamined life is not worth living.

09:54.114 --> 09:55.896
fewer than I thought, wow, that's interesting.

09:56.977 --> 10:23.442
The unexamined life, so what I think he means by this is well, any number of things, but it's the recognition that we must put a magnifying glass over our very lives, and life generally needs to be understood, like generally as in like through the sciences or understanding what's going on out there, but especially like interior, like our interior lives must be understood and we must

10:23.714 --> 10:26.838
think and examine what's really going on.

10:26.898 --> 10:39.694
And he says, and I happen to agree with him, that this is the only way to virtue, to becoming people of character, people who live lives that are just and right.

10:42.498 --> 10:52.050
And so I'd contend that the 40-year-old Christian, who is still acting like a toddler, is almost certainly living an unexamined life.

10:53.378 --> 10:58.523
And my hope today is to draw you into living the examined life.

10:59.324 --> 11:04.870
Psalm 139, 23 to 24 is our text, and it goes like this.

11:05.431 --> 11:09.995
Search me, oh God, and know my heart.

11:12.158 --> 11:16.823
Try me, test me, and know my thoughts.

11:18.684 --> 11:20.146
See if there is any

11:20.450 --> 11:24.276
grieve this way or offensive way in me?

11:25.258 --> 11:28.283
Is there anything that offends my brothers and sisters?

11:29.304 --> 11:32.409
Is there anything that offends you, God, in my way?

11:33.852 --> 11:44.649
And then lead me in ways, paths that are everlasting, the kind of path that goes on and on and on.

11:45.871 --> 11:47.474
Like, that's what I want, right?

11:47.842 --> 11:52.187
And so this passage is an invitation into the examined life.

11:52.708 --> 11:58.494
Someone who is quite literally, David here, asking God, God, I want you to look in.

11:58.514 --> 12:09.507
I open my heart up to you and I need you to see what's in there and I need to show me what the path is that is the righteous path.

12:10.208 --> 12:15.474
The path that leads to life, like real life, abundant life, the good life,

12:16.386 --> 12:18.168
Because only you can show me that.

12:18.869 --> 12:20.472
And so God, search me.

12:21.333 --> 12:22.034
Know my heart.

12:22.915 --> 12:23.676
Know my mind.

12:23.716 --> 12:27.201
I want it to be set on you.

12:32.147 --> 12:40.118
Socrates also said other things in his life, one of which is quite simpler yet.

12:40.819 --> 12:41.560
Know thyself.

12:42.161 --> 12:42.962
Know thyself.

12:43.042 --> 12:53.493
On Baylor's campus where I was a student for a time, you'd walk across this one path and there'd be like famous quotes everywhere.

12:53.533 --> 13:01.702
And one of the prominent spot on the ground etched in the ground was Socrates, know thyself, right?

13:01.982 --> 13:02.623
Know thyself.

13:04.365 --> 13:09.330
This one I think is a life pursuit.

13:10.242 --> 13:15.768
Knowing thyself, it seems like something that you should just inherently be able to do.

13:15.808 --> 13:18.751
It seems like it on the surface.

13:18.771 --> 13:22.155
I know me better than you know me, you think.

13:23.416 --> 13:26.199
And yet we all know that this isn't actually entirely true.

13:26.259 --> 13:36.490
Think of you as an 18-year-old or maybe your 18-year-old child or somebody who's getting ready to move into the world as an adult.

13:38.252 --> 13:39.954
Do they know themselves?

13:40.770 --> 13:41.271
Well, sorta.

13:42.913 --> 13:51.547
But if they're being honest, or if I'm being honest at age 18, I should probably ask mom and dad a little more about, well, who am I?

13:52.588 --> 13:54.031
What was I like as a kid?

13:54.111 --> 13:56.895
And what are the things that make me come alive?

13:56.975 --> 13:58.778
And where are my weaknesses?

13:58.878 --> 14:00.721
And what are my gifts in life?

14:00.921 --> 14:06.450
And all of these things, these are not self-evident.

14:06.946 --> 14:09.009
You don't just sit down and write them out.

14:09.530 --> 14:18.241
I mean, some people are good at knowing this, better at knowing this than other people, but knowing thyself is actually a lifelong task.

14:18.682 --> 14:33.542
One that I would encourage you on because I think it directly connects with what we're talking about today, the examined life and the ability to ask God, search me and know me in some ways it starts with knowing oneself.

14:34.784 --> 14:36.306
And now you might be thinking, Eric,

14:36.386 --> 14:41.432
Why are you quoting this Western philosopher who was not a Christian or a Jew?

14:41.913 --> 14:42.954
He's not in our canon.

14:42.974 --> 14:43.956
He's not in our Bible.

14:44.276 --> 14:52.286
And so I want to now submit to you a few other Christian authors through the ages.

14:52.346 --> 15:04.722
And here again is a pitch to come to Wednesday nights, emotionally healthy spiritually, where in chapter two, he lays these out in a way that even stunned me.

15:05.026 --> 15:08.310
And so let me quote for you from our tradition.

15:08.390 --> 15:18.721
Starting with St. Augustine, he says this, how can you draw close to God when you are far from your own self?

15:20.643 --> 15:27.450
And then he prayed, Grant Lord, that I may know myself, that I may know you.

15:27.490 --> 15:30.974
There's a lot there.

15:33.677 --> 15:34.738
Fast forwarding through time.

15:35.490 --> 15:39.075
Meister Eckhart, 13th century, Dominican.

15:40.476 --> 15:46.044
None can know God who does not first know himself.

15:47.806 --> 15:54.475
None can know God who does not first know himself.

15:54.495 --> 15:58.059
Fast forwarding again, St. Teresa of Avila.

15:59.581 --> 16:03.186
Almost all problems in the spiritual life

16:03.906 --> 16:11.800
stem from a lack of self-knowledge.

16:11.820 --> 16:21.938
Lastly, for the Calvinists in our midst and an ode to Clint, he and I often talk about our

16:22.114 --> 16:27.079
reformed brothers and sisters and the Reformation period.

16:27.860 --> 16:34.006
Calvin himself might be the last person, if you know anything about Calvin, who you would expect to say something like this.

16:34.646 --> 16:44.676
And yet here it is in the opening lines of his epic tone, the Institutes of Christian Religion, he says the following.

16:46.018 --> 16:50.482
Our wisdom consists almost entirely of two parts.

16:50.978 --> 16:54.982
the knowledge of God and of ourselves.

16:56.184 --> 17:10.440
But as these are connected together by many ties, it is not easy to determine which of the two knowledge of ourselves or knowledge of God precedes and gives birth to the other.

17:13.783 --> 17:19.730
To know oneself, to know thyself, I do believe

17:20.066 --> 17:24.412
is a necessary requirement, certainly of living the examined life.

17:25.333 --> 17:32.423
I think of living a mature Christian life, a life that is transformed by Jesus.

17:32.464 --> 17:45.522
And in part because it starts with knowing yourself so that you can take off the false ways in which you think you need to perform in the world.

17:46.274 --> 18:02.962
So that instead of performing for other people because you think they need you to be someone, a pastor or a NASA scientist or some top exec at the DOD or whatever role you play in life.

18:05.245 --> 18:06.247
That's not who you are.

18:07.589 --> 18:12.978
Or maybe it's like your wealth or your possessions

18:13.218 --> 18:16.423
And you say, well, if I have these, then this is who I am.

18:16.443 --> 18:18.426
And I would say, no.

18:18.467 --> 18:21.291
No, this is not who you are.

18:22.974 --> 18:25.498
There's something under there that is much more important.

18:26.179 --> 18:29.565
You must know yourself because that is not who you are.

18:29.885 --> 18:31.969
That's just a mask sitting in front of you.

18:35.294 --> 18:40.242
So in order to transform, we must begin with knowing thyself.

18:42.626 --> 18:44.929
The solution, of course, is from our passage today.

18:44.969 --> 18:46.030
I'll read it again.

18:46.070 --> 18:49.074
Psalm 139, 23 to 24.

18:50.156 --> 18:51.137
Search me, O God.

18:52.098 --> 18:54.201
Search me and know my heart.

18:54.641 --> 19:03.793
Try me and know my thoughts and see if there's anything grievous in my ways and lead me in your ways which are everlasting.

19:04.494 --> 19:10.802
And I want you to notice perhaps the most important part of all of this, which is to say that

19:11.010 --> 19:15.255
that David here isn't just saying, I'm searching within myself.

19:16.176 --> 19:17.878
I do think this is important to know thyself.

19:18.358 --> 19:21.242
It requires some sort of interior introspection.

19:22.083 --> 19:25.507
But he's actually calling on God to search him.

19:25.547 --> 19:30.272
And he is saying, God, I want to think your thoughts.

19:31.413 --> 19:39.122
And you can even imagine David himself envisioning, how does God see me?

19:39.266 --> 19:51.703
From God's point of view, when he looks down at my life and my actions, and he looks into my heart, what does he find there?

19:53.245 --> 19:54.567
What does he see me doing?

19:55.649 --> 19:56.750
What does he see me thinking?

19:58.733 --> 20:05.202
And David goes on, he says, may it not be anything that brings offense to others and to you,

20:05.954 --> 20:11.120
And maybe it may be a thing that leads me down paths of righteousness.

20:13.503 --> 20:16.766
This almost is asking God to do the searching.

20:17.647 --> 20:22.112
And he is searching himself through the eyes of God.

20:23.934 --> 20:30.182
And so he might think back on his day when he stubbed his toe and he might say, God, I wonder what you thought of that.

20:32.164 --> 20:34.066
Or when he stormed out on his boss.

20:34.562 --> 20:36.564
God, I wonder what you thought of that.

20:38.406 --> 20:49.659
Or when someone iced out their spouse by not speaking to them for days, the psalmist or you might say, search me.

20:50.420 --> 20:51.141
Know my heart.

20:51.861 --> 20:53.063
Help me see the world.

20:53.543 --> 20:56.406
Help me see my world as you see it.

20:59.009 --> 21:03.154
Because here's the truth about you and about me.

21:03.778 --> 21:07.062
and about all humans.

21:07.082 --> 21:12.869
We are the iceberg that is on the cover of this study that we're doing together, right?

21:13.369 --> 21:19.697
And the iceberg, it looks like, as we all know iceberg, it kind of has this spot that's on the top of the water.

21:19.717 --> 21:24.002
And then you've got this rest of it that's way under the water, right?

21:24.463 --> 21:27.787
And we often think of our lives as that which sits up here.

21:27.847 --> 21:30.610
That is not the whole of your life.

21:30.754 --> 21:34.478
It feels like it is, it looks like it is, but that is not the whole of your life.

21:35.159 --> 21:45.631
And if there's anything I've learned over many years of study and thinking about how humans work and how scripture works and how theology works, it's this.

21:46.272 --> 21:49.415
A number of years ago, I did a study on the seven deadly sins.

21:50.436 --> 21:59.026
And two people, turns out, can commit one act, which sits up here, murder, we'll say, murder.

22:00.258 --> 22:04.322
The underneath part of it all is two very different things.

22:05.384 --> 22:11.510
So you might be tempted to think, oh, well, this problem, this person has the problem of, of murder.

22:13.933 --> 22:20.881
When in reality, one of them has a problem of anger, one of the deadly sins, right?

22:20.901 --> 22:25.225
And they have allowed anger to take over their heart on a regular basis.

22:25.786 --> 22:29.490
And it was the anger that's sitting under the surface

22:30.434 --> 22:35.221
that drives them to do this awful heinous act.

22:35.241 --> 22:44.794
And then a different person, well, they might not actually have that much anger, except in the moment, of course, but instead, what do they have?

22:44.854 --> 22:46.597
Well, maybe they have envy.

22:47.798 --> 22:52.926
They're so envious of this person and it's eating them alive.

22:56.871 --> 22:58.834
And it causes them to do the heinous act.

22:59.746 --> 23:03.210
And so you might be thinking, well, Eric, what does this have to do with our message today?

23:03.230 --> 23:04.671
It has everything to do with the message.

23:04.992 --> 23:08.396
Because if you say to God, search me and know me.

23:08.436 --> 23:11.939
And your answer is, okay, now I won't commit murder.

23:12.320 --> 23:14.582
You've not done enough work.

23:17.385 --> 23:19.087
Search me and know me.

23:19.147 --> 23:24.754
Why am I so angry underneath the surface?

23:25.514 --> 23:28.818
What is causing that anger and God, how?

23:28.930 --> 23:30.812
Can I give that over to you?

23:31.213 --> 23:42.427
How can I allow that to be transformed by you so that the anger is no longer causing me to even consider something as terrible as murder?

23:43.509 --> 23:46.132
Or likewise, envy.

23:46.172 --> 23:51.539
God, figure out this envy that, search me and know me.

23:51.579 --> 23:57.266
That envy is sitting under there and I cannot do, I can't figure out why it's there.

23:57.762 --> 24:08.320
But I'm feeling it, and I know it is, and I don't want it there anymore, because the last thing I want to happen is to accidentally murder somebody.

24:10.183 --> 24:11.125
I shouldn't laugh about that.

24:13.829 --> 24:14.931
Hopefully you get the idea.

24:14.951 --> 24:21.883
This prayer, this Psalm 139 prayer, seems so simple, right?

24:22.364 --> 24:23.506
Search me and know me.

24:24.226 --> 24:34.457
But my suggestion to you is if you're doing this on a regular basis, what you're going to find is God will begin to reveal more and more and more.

24:34.497 --> 24:53.298
And as you plumb the depths under the water and get below the surface of it all, you'll realize there's a lot of you left to be explored and understood and healed and it will change everything.

24:53.762 --> 24:56.265
It will change the way you work in your relationships.

24:56.586 --> 25:05.238
It will change how you treat the people around you, your children, your spouse, your mom, your dad, your coworkers, your friends, your church mates.

25:06.560 --> 25:07.621
It will change everything.

25:10.605 --> 25:14.591
If again, you allow God to search me and know me.

25:16.634 --> 25:20.539
All right, so I am going to leave us with a tool.

25:21.981 --> 25:22.642
I've gone.

25:23.490 --> 25:26.955
and I've given you a cheat sheet and it's on your bulletin.

25:27.996 --> 25:36.848
And the cheat sheet says this, if you see at the top on the backside where there's normally a notes section, I've essentially written the notes for you.

25:37.449 --> 25:49.746
Here's my expectation that you will all put this very important place in your pocket, next to your bedside, in your Bible,

25:51.650 --> 25:57.616
And that you will consider doing this on a at least weekly.

25:58.297 --> 26:02.221
I would recommend, I should say daily basis is what you should be aiming for.

26:02.901 --> 26:04.663
It is called The Examine.

26:05.624 --> 26:08.987
It's by a guy named St. Ignatius of Loyola.

26:09.868 --> 26:12.471
And this is something I've talked about before.

26:13.132 --> 26:19.538
If you were here when we talked about Pete Gregg's How to Pray book, I mentioned it then.

26:20.066 --> 26:26.015
And it is in that book, and the four Rs are from him.

26:26.055 --> 26:28.900
And so I'm simply repeating this for you.

26:29.861 --> 26:31.965
But the prayer is quite simple, really.

26:32.005 --> 26:36.251
It is a prayer of examination, and it goes like this.

26:36.632 --> 26:48.370
At the end of a long day, you lay your head down, or maybe you just kind of get away for five minutes from the kids and everybody else, and you just spend some time in silence.

26:48.738 --> 26:52.183
and you begin by replaying the events of the day.

26:53.024 --> 27:03.037
Nonjudgmental, you don't need to like, you know, go through and every bit, just kind of see, just start thinking about what happened that day.

27:04.739 --> 27:18.578
Where were you and who did you bump into and what comes up, like what was important, what caused some like really positive emotions maybe and some, what caused you anxiety or frustration

27:18.754 --> 27:20.577
You know, just think through the day.

27:21.979 --> 27:24.643
Step two then is to rejoice.

27:25.645 --> 27:47.378
And for some of you, this is maybe the most important work you'll do because it's quite likely that a few of us in here struggle with thinking that the world is darker than it actually is, that it's not a good place, that maybe God is absent from it and is not showing up in your life.

27:48.354 --> 28:03.470
And the challenge of this second rejoicing part is as you go through that day, you think to yourself, well, this was a really beautiful moment where a friend of mine told me a compliment and it meant a lot to me.

28:04.872 --> 28:08.095
And then this other part was so nice.

28:08.195 --> 28:14.642
I had a success at work today that I didn't expect and that felt really good.

28:16.002 --> 28:20.226
And then you go through your day and you rejoice and you thank God for these things.

28:21.688 --> 28:36.884
And there's something in that part of the practice that for those of you who may struggle with an absentee God will begin to realize that God is showing up in your life on a pretty regular basis if you have eyes to see it.

28:39.426 --> 28:42.930
And then there's the third one, which is the repentance part.

28:43.970 --> 28:52.578
And this is where you take stock of your day and you say, okay, this happened, and I wish I could have a redo.

28:54.400 --> 28:56.202
I wish I could do that part again.

28:57.383 --> 28:59.645
And it might be a big thing, right?

28:59.665 --> 29:07.492
It might be like a knockdown drag out fight with your mom or something, and you wished you could just do it all over again.

29:08.313 --> 29:09.514
But it might be something small.

29:10.355 --> 29:13.298
And my guess is over time, if you're doing this regularly,

29:13.570 --> 29:20.657
It's actually the small things that will become most important because that's where the stuff under the surface lives.

29:20.877 --> 29:38.774
It's the small things you begin to notice about the way you're walking through the world and the way you respond to somebody with an unnecessary negativity or you respond to somebody thinking the worst of them rather than thinking of the best in them.

29:40.255 --> 29:43.378
And then in that moment you get to ask yourself, well, why did I do that?

29:45.250 --> 29:47.654
Why did I not open my heart to this person?

29:48.796 --> 29:53.143
Why didn't I give them the grace that they deserved and that Jesus would have given them?

29:54.285 --> 29:58.312
What has happened in my life to cause me to be that person?

29:58.332 --> 30:03.100
And then, step four, reboot.

30:04.463 --> 30:05.384
Anything about tomorrow?

30:06.326 --> 30:11.154
The next day, and you say to yourself, well, tomorrow is going to be different.

30:12.034 --> 30:19.803
And I am going to pivot out of that way of being that holds me down and that requires the repentance.

30:20.704 --> 30:28.554
And I am going to be a different person tomorrow with the help of God and the Holy Spirit working through me.

30:29.635 --> 30:30.897
I am changing.

30:33.180 --> 30:33.700
So this is it.

30:33.981 --> 30:35.242
This is the daily examine.

30:35.763 --> 30:37.505
This is the full name, the daily examine.

30:38.326 --> 30:41.810
And it's something that I would encourage you to

30:41.922 --> 30:45.166
Hold on to very simple little practice.

30:46.147 --> 30:49.431
But I think it is the beginning of an examined life.

30:53.416 --> 30:57.240
Now I'm going to give you the chance to actually practice it in real time.

30:59.503 --> 31:00.885
We're going to take communion here.

31:01.906 --> 31:11.858
And if there's ever a time to think about examining one's life, well, Paul tells us very clearly as we approach

31:12.066 --> 31:25.380
the table, we must search within ourselves, asking God for forgiveness, asking if there's anything in between me and God that he might rid us of that.

31:27.162 --> 31:30.986
This is a wonderful time to practice the exam and in your own life.

31:31.787 --> 31:38.354
And maybe you're thinking back through today, but maybe yesterday, rather, maybe it's this last week,

31:38.946 --> 31:59.429
And just kind of go through, as you're holding the bread and the cup in your hands, and you're waiting for us to take communion together, and you're holding the body and blood of Christ, and you're looking into the face of Jesus, and he's looking back at you, what is standing between the two of you?

32:00.931 --> 32:07.378
Confess that to him, reboot, and prepare for the next day.

32:08.482 --> 32:09.203
Let's pray together.

32:11.146 --> 32:19.557
Heavenly Father, I pray a prayer of blessing unto those who are gathered right now.

32:21.400 --> 32:26.067
I would ask that you open their hearts to what it is you're doing in them.

32:27.509 --> 32:37.202
Stir in them anew, a sense that you are alive and well in their hearts and lives, and you desire change.

32:38.370 --> 33:02.162
You desire it so much, God, that you send your son, Jesus Christ, to die, and to be raised again from the dead, that we might, too, live new lives, lives of transformation, lives of resurrection, lives that have died to the old self and been raised anew.

33:05.306 --> 33:08.050
So today, Lord, we come confessing

33:08.802 --> 33:16.258
We come examining, and most of all, we come giving thanks for Jesus Christ, our Lord, and our Savior.

33:17.360 --> 33:21.589
We ask a blessing on the bread and to the cup.

33:22.190 --> 33:23.132
In Christ's name we pray.

33:23.793 --> 33:24.114
Amen.

